Implement the private `partition/2` function. It splits `items` into `n` sub-lists
as evenly as possible — one per worker — and returns them as a list of `n` chunks in
worker-id order (chunk `0` first).

Distribution rules:

- Let `total` be the number of items, `base_size = div(total, n)`, and
  `extras = rem(total, n)`. The first `extras` chunks receive `base_size + 1` items
  each; every remaining chunk receives `base_size` items. This spreads any remainder
  across the earliest workers, so chunk sizes differ by at most one and empty chunks
  appear naturally when `n` exceeds the number of items.
- Consume `items` in order, slicing off each chunk from the front of what's left
  (e.g. with `Enum.split/2`) so no item is duplicated or dropped.
- Each chunk must be sorted into descending priority order before being returned, so
  that every worker's local queue starts with its most urgent item at the head. Reuse
  the existing `sort_desc/1` helper for this.
- The returned list must contain exactly `n` chunks, in ascending worker-id order.

